Given $\triangle ABC \sim \triangle PAQ$, we know that $\angle ACB \cong \angle QAP$ and $\angle ABC \cong \angle QPA$. Similarly, from $\triangle ABQ \sim \triangle QCP$, we know that $\angle AQB \cong \angle CPQ$ and $\angle QBA \cong \angle QPC$.

From the information provided, we know that $m\angle BAC = 70^\circ$, so we can find:
\begin{align} m\angle ABC &= 180^{\circ} - m\angle BAC - m\angle ACB \\ m\angle ABC &= 180^{\circ} - 70^{\circ} - x \end{align}
Additionally, we know that $\angle ABC \cong \angle QPA$, so we can write:
\begin{align} \angle QPA &= 180^{\circ} - 70^{\circ} - x \end{align}

Since we are looking to find $m\angle PQC$, we can look to $\triangle CPQ$. By writing out the angles in terms of $x$, we find:
\begin{align} m\angle PQC &= m\angle CPQ + m\angle QPC \\ m\angle PQC &= (180^{\circ} - x) + (180^{\circ} - x) \\ m\angle PQC &= 2(180^{\circ} - x) \end{align}

Solving (2) gives $x=110^\circ$, which substituted into (3) yields:
\begin{align} m\angle PQC &= 2(180^{\circ} - 110^{\circ}) \\ m\angle PQC &= 2 \times 70^{\circ} \\ m\angle PQC &= 140^{\circ} \end{align}

Thus, $m\angle PQC = 140^\circ$.

